 aThis book is a powerful narrative of how six women experienced their lives alongside their desire to overcome the challenging and empowering nature of the English language. The volume shares who they are as transnational and mobile women living in the midst of linguistic privilege and marginalization. It is one outcome of a research project and the lived experiences which surround and influence (and were influenced by) it. The author documents how she and her research partners began studying what had drawn them to US TESOL programs, and how English was and is a symbol of power and privilege, a symbol of educational access and a pursuit of equity, yet, at times, is also a symbol of linguistic marginalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teaching (Higher)xForeign speakers. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxSocial aspects. 0aEnglish language--Study and teaching (Higher)--Foreign speakers. 0aEnglish teacherszEast AsiavBiography. 0aEnglish teacherszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aWomen teacherszEast AsiavBiography. 0aWomen teacherszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aELT.  aEnglish language teaching .  aFeminism.  aFeminist theory.  aIdentity.  aLanguage teacher identity.  aLanguage teachers.  aPrivilege and marginalization.  aRace, Class and Gender connection.  aRace.  aWomen’s narratives.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066312908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMultiLingual Matters eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060670640uhttps://doi.org/10.21832/978178309873640uhttps://www.degruyter.c